posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114102256
>best amp sim for guitar and/or bass? maybe i'm just retarded but i can't get a good tone out of logic's default ones.
I have used Logic's amps and I found that for a hard rock/metal tone, I needed to do a couple of EQ moves. I think I did this.
1. High shelf boost before the amp.
2. Pretty big mid-scoop after the amp.
3. Pretty big bass boost around 70-100hz, depending on your tuning.
4. High-cut the really bright frequencies, at least above 10k, but possibly even lower than that.
5. You might want a boost around 6k for brightness.
6. Precise notch cuts to dampen resonant frequencies.

Remember that amp sims are really just algorithmic distortion and filters in a box. You can usually get a good tone out of anything with conscious EQ moves.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114086447
Not a bad ranking. I can give you a quick rundown on the
>Dave Holland
Fusion bassist. One of the most important members of Miles' late 60s / very early 70s period. Also has a couple records with Chick Corea and Joe Henderson
>Michael Henderson
More or less the same thing. Jazz Funk bassist, prominently worked with Miles in the mid 70s. Also has a few credits with other Jazz-Funk musicians like Norman Connors and Johnnie Taylor
>Miroslav Virtuous
More on the avant-garde side of Fusion. Most prominent sidework is with Weather Reports early era and Chick Corea's mid 70s solo albums.
>Alphonso Johnson
Arguably the most prominent of the group. Main credits aside from his solo career and Weather Report era (74-77), he has quite a few contributions to well known Jazz and Pop acts (Paul Simon, Phil Collins, George Duke, Quincy Jones, and Bob James just to name a few)

a category Rateyourmusic uses for jazz that sounds like it might be released by ECM

an artifact of jazz being so far away from mainstream that people mostly stopped giving new jazz styles names after fusion hit

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114090059
ECM is generally known for releasing music that is on the slow and mellow side of things. They also release some contemporary classical music, so you'll find they have some third stream as well. You're rarely if ever gonna hear something from that sounds high energy, and all their albums have a very subtle but sterile production to them as well. The only way you'll ever properly understand it is to listen to a few records of theirs yourself.

I see HIP less as a competitor to the way classical music is performed in general and more as an experiment in trying to emulate the past. They're two different markets that touch upon the same type of work. Most HIP focuses on baroque music and uses the harpsichord and viola. Instruments that have a different vibe and feel compared to their successors. It is only natural that certain groups would like to revive that feeling only those instruments could provide. However, HIP can delve into the realm of the autist if it's something like refusing to play Beethoven on anything other than a fortepiano. Again, I don't believe that HIP is really doing anything that harmful.

If only you knew how great it was...20-9 years ago, before the bums showed up, before it became a "quiet suburb" for Dallas's foreign tech and healthcare workers, Denton was at its zenith and every music lover agreed it was the new Austin. At all times of day, every day of the year, at all locations, you heard live music, every kind. You could do a walk of the downtown area and hear 7 different bands playing in the stores and courthouse lawn. There would be all kinds of street performer musicians out jamming in the alley between the downtown theater and Cartwright's ranch house. There was one day I saw a string quintet on the lawn, a straight-ahead jazz group in Jupiter House, a dixieland jazz group in another coffee shop that used to be there, a Steely Dan cover band in LSA burger's rooftop bar, a few guys playing hangs/handpans in the alley, the best local band I've ever seen (Ashley Gatta and the Free People) at Eastside (oak street), a Texas blues trio at Sweetwater, and Brave Combo's singer's solo polka band in a defunct place called Banter (now the 940s). That wasn't even a festival or anything. Just an ordinary Friday. You don't see any of that anymore. It used to be like SxSW every other week in Denton. And it wasn't a promotion or anything. >>114102823
Listened to the whole album
That beat drop on track 4 was really good, wasnt expecting that. Those drums and synthd make me think of Orchestral Manouevres at the Dark. Maybe my favorite part of this EP
Vocals are a bit buried in all tracks. Nice bass on track 2. Track 1 isnt really a strong opener to the album I think.
Something about the tracks overall make me not really get into the vibe of the album and engage with it completely. It seems a bit monotonous maybe, like the album is just going through the motions and no part is really different than another. For example, track 2 has a synth solo but when it hapoens everything else (bass, guitar, back synth, drums especially) is just doing the same thing they were already doing. That can be me not being familiar with the style, but I feel the tracks would be better with something to grab the listener. Maybe develop the ideas you have in the arrangement a bit, what I get from it is no moment really standing out. It could help giving some relief (in the architectural sense). Track 3 for example is a bit better in this regard, but even with some cool different synth stuff being introduced the rest of it is still is very much of the same and the vocals being buried doesnt help.
Anyway I like the elements here I just think they could fit together in a better way. Im also not a huge fan of the vague/suggestive lyrics
The final track is a good album closer, maybe the guitar could let itself go a bit tho and play around the synth. But the guitar notes complement the synths really well here

Primus is good and does not suck... in their first album. Claypool is also involved in more graditional stuff and I would say he got bored of Primus' schtick almost immediately. I respect that Primus is intentionally neglecting or outright raping 4 aspects of music to service 1 aspect in particular song to song. I also respect that Les is a shitty singer who you "get used to" rather than eventually discovering or really ever coming to appreciate some core nugget of vocal talent. The reason I'm typing all this is almost nil, but if there is one, it's that purposefully doing something "wrong" for the sake of art is not "bad". The Primus Sucks meme was Les, an eternal hipster and pseud, ruthlessly mocking "wrong note: sounded mcbad" NPC's for that. I will take Les' weird child molester faux-whisper tone as part of the art and enjoy that such an absurd thing exists.

When I first heard Primus I thought "this is the future of rock". It turns out I am a full on autistic retard, but I still think big wig marketeers missed out on some good public consciousness fuckerization by leaning into their 6 popularly trained-in money melodies instead of straight up redefining what is 'supposed" to sound good and in that way sending goy into a pit of God-less discovery. I have realized that not only would they rather keep their cash cow chord progressions to re-market endlessly in every genre and phony boxed-in musical movement, but that tampering with trained positive/negative associations in any way that distorts the sense of a "correct/incorrect", "good/bad' dichotomy represents a loss of control over us on a deep level. Deep in the sense that it is trained in without words and outside of the scope of direct internal language dialogue thoughtform that is all most people have to check or police themselves and their mental habits.

I think about suicide daily. Primus is great though.

>>114111982
'd love to form a hardcore band with a sound that has some metal influences. Some of my current inspirations for writing in this style are: Buggin, Zulu, Mortality Rate, Thirdface, Minor Threat, Full of Hell, Thou, Mizmor, Defeater, Between the Buried and Me, Ego Death, Spurr, Dystopia, Move BHC, Squirrel Bait, The Black Dahlia Murder, Panopticon. The stuff I've been writing in this vein is written with live shows in mind (having fun parts to dance to), some chaotic and noisy parts, while also having some kind of melodic death metal/black metal sounding parts in there). I like breakdowns, two-steps, some old school hardcore/punk sounds similar to Minor Threat, and also more intricate techy metal stuff, doom/death sounding riffs, and dissonant chaotic parts. I currently play guitar in this style but would also be open to playing bass! I'd love to find a drummer, vocalist, and a bassist/another guitarist to play this stuff with.

I've also been writing some kinda indie-ish stuff for awhile with lyrics. Some artists that have been inspiring me in this realm recently are: MJ Lenderman, Wednesday, Devin Champlain, my bloody valentine, Knifeplay, Big Thief, Horse Jumper of Love, Careen, Squirrel Bait, Oh, Rose, Smashing Pumpkins. It tends to be like an indie rock, sometimes country/folk sound with some heavier parts inspired by shoegaze, grunge, and punk music. Currently I play this stuff with a friend of mine who plays mandolin and violin and I play guitar and sing. I'm open to whatever other kind of instrumentalist is interested in playing this. Would love to find a drummer, bassist, and some more string or keyboard players for this project!

Lastly I think it would be rad to play in band that is mostly instrumental that plays some noise inspired rock music. I like godspeed you black emperor, slint, mogwai, roy montgomery, caroline to name a few. I write some loosely structured music in this kind of sound that would be cool to experiment with.

I will be totally honest. RM's album roll-out was quite overwhelming, it had so many interviews (some magazines I have yet to finish reading), small live performances, documentaries and activities overall, he actually chosed a more packed schedule than his two predecessors (J-Hope and Jin).

So, I wanted at some point to do a post to talk a bit about the album and its artistry, but as the interviews where he went deep into the explanations kept coming out, I thought to myself, it's going to be hard to digest everything but also to summarize it in a post, so I pushed it aside.

But there, I just saw the reaction

of FormOfTherapy to "Wild Flower", and I had tears in my eyes. Adding to the context, I only watch a handful of reactors whose reactions I personally enjoy, and FormOfTherapy is among them.

I was delighted to see that he was probably the only one (among the reactors I've seen) who had a similar reaction to mine, namely emotional.

So, I'm not going to do a deep dive right now on the album, but it's just an appreciation for this particular song and RM.

I believe sometimes k-pop fans and most ARMYs don't realize that RM was an upcoming KHH prince. He was barely 16 when he was invited by Korean KHH legends on featured songs, which was an incredible honor so young. Later, he was rejected by this industry and community where he had a bright future I might add, for choosing another industry, which also rejected him because he didn't meet the idol standards and restrictions.

He struggled a lot on how he defines himself, an idol or rapper or an artist ? He received and still receives daily a lot of hate.

cont.

>>114111432
And despite everything, RM is without a doubt for me an incredible artist for his generation. I mean, we often define BTS as generational pop stars, recently they were even called "Princes of Pop". But RM, strike me as this one-of-a-kind artist, for the Korean industry but also across the world. I remember Wale saying he could be among the biggest in the American industry if he really wanted to, and that was back in 2017 when Wale mostly only knew his artistry through his work with him, and those lyrics.

Because we have to talk about it, the words, the lyrics he creates are just superb, he can express so much using only a few lines.

"These days most people don't listen to lyrics anymore, but I want to buck the trend. In the era of music streaming, I want to focus on albums ... as someone who wanted to become a poet, the audible feel of the words and the beauty of lyrics are important." - RM [MOTS: Persona Vlive]

His mindset is still the same, as he said it many times in his recent interviews. That's why his title track is so long when songs are getting shorter because of fast consumption, that's also why he asked the fans to pay attention to the lyrics of his album.

This is where I come back to Wild Flower, for him this track is an explosion. It's not a song made for "comfort" strictly speaking, but where he expressed himself, just like fireworks, explosion of emotions, that's also why he chose Youjeen and her voice.

Wild Flower MV became the most beautiful of 2022 to me. The visuals mixed with the lyrics are just amazing. It really is an experience. I haven't felt this in a while. Even Astronaut and Yet To Come which was highly emotional as an ARMY didn't got me as much as Wild Flower did, like it went deeper than feelings as a fan, but as a human being. I don't know if that makes sense, but I felt it deep in my soul.

cont.

Lemme tell you. My dad grew up in the Bay Area in the 70s. Rock was serious business, nay, a religion, for white teens back then. Among the kids he knew, a wide range of listening tastes was represented. There were Stones fans and Zeppelin fans, and fans of Montrose, UFO, Aerosmith, Thin Lizzy, and other hard rock bands. There were prog kids who were bumping Yes, Rush, and Tull. There were kids who listened to the critical darlings like the Stooges and Television, and yes, even the New York Dolls.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Capitalism isn't defined by trade or even markets. It's defined by the ability to accumulate capital. The most effective ways to do that are paying your workers less than the value of their labor, and making passive income through things like investments and being a landlord.

Capitalism is based on exploitation, almost by definition. However, the extant forms of socialism are all rooted in Soviet-esque Leninism, which is even worse. Market mechanisms are important to efficiently send goods where they're demanded. Innovation is also important.

There is an old economic system that economists are starting to rediscover called mutualism, which might hold some answers. This might be counter-intuitive, but it was basically free market socialism. Firms were collectively owned and democratically run by the workers. It would also put community supports in the hands of communities themselves, so people would control the funds helping each other.

While mutualism would more fairly distribute resources, I think there needs to be a more stable social safety net, so I'd want something like left-mutualism or social mutualism or something like that, which isn't a thing.

posts.com:
Back home from the Mayhem/Emperor concert, nothing but greatness.

It was a full production show for both bands, literally DVD-tier.
Mayhem had 4 standards hanging from the ceiling with old pics of Dead, Euronymous, Hellhammer and Necrobutcher, they changed the background flag three times with each part of the set.
They started with post Eurodeath material with a Daemon flag, had some songs like My Death and Crystallized Pain in Deconstruction.
Then switched to DMDS and got hooded up, played Buried by Time and Dust, Pagan Fears, Life Eternal and Freezing Moon
Then there comes the red flag for Deathcrush, they changed clothes again to old school shit (Teloch and Attila were wearing battle vests) and they played ALL fucking Deathcrush.
I nearly fucking came and yes, even Silvester Anfang.

Unlike what some anon said, they weren't drunk enough to fuck up anything, very well done, good stage presence.

Emperor were disgustingly perfect, they literally didn't miss a goddamn note. They played practically every classic, no real surprise like Mayhem but what the fuck man, I just wanted pros playing some good black metal and they sure fucking delivered.

They were playing with mostly white/green/blue lights, when the lights all turned red and the riff from I am the Black Wizard started I fucking busted lads, it was something I'll remember till Death takes me home.

So it looks like OP, or maybe some of you in this thread (a much smaller number than total posts), would like /mu/ to be less dead. Here's a few ideas on what you can do to try and improve the quality of our board.
1. Hide threads you don't want. I regularly have 40+ hidden threads on /mu/. A few of them are legitimate and active topics that I'm not personally interested in but the vast majority of them are slides, shills, or improperly structured to attract engagement. Frogpost? Hide it. Copypasta? Hide it.
>but I can sage and dunk on retards
It doesn't help. The people who fall into pitfall threads are not going to be persuaded by your epic putdowns. They are background noise that you can do nothing about apart from ignore. Do not engage with threads you do not want on the board, full stop.
2. Don't engage with non-music content. Don't reply, don't complain, don't acknowledge. This is our meta thread but it's already becoming an off-topic /pol/ thread just by virtue of people being annoyed with /pol/ posters. They can form small colonies in threads but they're going to get more engagement elsewhere and if they starve they leave.
3. Give (You)'s when people make good observations or put effort into posts. This is not the ideal format for music discussion, you're already fighting an uphill battle on the topic. Most posters don't have the attention span to put more than two sentences into a post. You need to recognize when there's another human in the thread.
4. Start from the bottom. Often a good fledgling thread exists somewhere on page 6+ and is getting aged out by frogposter OPs, copypasta ("What kind of person do you imagine?") or another stupid Beatles/Beach Boys joke. /mu/ is a slower board. If a good topic gets a moderate amount of attention a thread can live for several days. If you don't bump that thread it may die before it gains momentum.

>>114106336
>What went wrong? It seems like AnCo can't make a single distinguishable tune anymore. Everything they did after MPP just kinda blends together in a chaotic noise soup.
I disagree. From CHz, New Town Burnout and Wide-Eyed are very distinct from one another. On the new album, which is far from being "unlistenable," Passer-By and Royal and Desire (a new highlight of their entire discography imo, even though I dislike the song title), also have their own feel.

>It's got me second guessing whether they were even good to begin with.
They were definitely great at one point, even if you aren't connecting with them now. One way I measure this kind of thing, besides just liking a track, is if you were to take away the band's performance and just keep the concepts, would the song still be strong? I've heard enough covers, rearrangements, and reimagined enough AnCo stuff myself that there's no question they had that spark of inspiration and made quality work. After the dumpster fire of Painting With, I was honestly thinking they were finally creatively bankrupt and should just hang it up, so much so that I wasn't hyped for Time Skiffs even with the live recordings of the tracks. I'm very glad that they delivered a solid album, even though it's somewhat middling. As others have said though, the next album is shaping up to be a possible new classic from them, as long as they don't mess it up in the studio as they've done a few times.
